From your code to distributed work.

Let's trace what happens when you write a chain like filter, then group-by, then count.

First, the driver builds a logical plan from your dataframe chain. This is just a description of the work, not the work itself.

Second, the Catalyst optimizer rewrites that plan. It pushes filters down so you read less data, it reorders joins, and it drops columns you never use.

Third, the optimized plan becomes a physical plan, and then a directed acyclic graph of stages.

Fourth, each stage splits into tasks. There is one task per partition.

Fifth, those tasks ship to the executors and run in parallel across their see-pee-you cores.

Now lock in three vocabulary words, because they show up constantly on the exam.

A job is what one action triggers. One count call produces one job.

A stage is a slice of work between shuffles. Every time Spark has to shuffle data across the network, it starts a new stage.

And a task is the smallest unit of work. It is one partition, processed by one executor core.
